reasoning\" field of EVERY reaction:\n   - Reference specific studies by author and year, e.g., \"(Huber & Wachtershauser, 1997)\"\n   - When multiple studies support a reaction, cite the most relevant ones\n   - If a reaction has no literature support from the provided research, explicitly state it is speculative and justify why it is necessary\n\n3. **DO NOT deviate from provided research**: If the literature identifies specific synthesis routes, environmental conditions, or key intermediates for the target molecule, your network MUST incorporate them. Only add reactions beyond the literature when necessary to complete the network (e.g., connecting known pathways)\n\n4. **ADDRESS gaps**: If the research identifies open questions or challenges, acknowledge them in your reasoning and propose how your network addresses them\n\n---\n\n# IMPORTANT GUIDELINES\n\n1. Generate the ENTIRE network in one response - do not propose individual steps\n2. Ensure molecules are defined BEFORE being referenced in reactions\n3. Every molecule ID in reactions must exist in the molecules array\n4. Hub molecules must have both incoming AND outgoing reactions\n5. Pathways must trace valid routes through the reaction network\n6. Consider realistic prebiotic conditions at each stage\n7. Include rate-limiting or key bottleneck reactions\n8. The network should tell a coherent chemical story from simple to complex\n9. Every Hydrothermal and Surface reaction MUST include mineral agents in the \"agents\" field\n10. Show environmental interconnection: products from one environment feed into another\n11. When deep research findings are provided, cite relevant literature in reaction reasoning fields\n", "user_message": "\nGenerate a SYNTHESIS NETWORK for: Arginine\n\nREQUIREMENTS:\n- Generate a bipartite network with molecule nodes and reaction nodes\n- Include 10 distinct pathways to the target\n- Identify 3-5 hub molecules where pathways converge\n- Ensure at least 8-15 molecules and 6-12 reactions\n- Show environmental interconnection: Hydrothermal \u2194 Surface \u2192 Biochemical\n- Every Hydrothermal and Surface reaction MUST include mineral agents in the \"agents\" field\n- Design multiple environmental routes to the same target where possible\n\nOutput the complete network as JSON following the schema in your instructions.\n\n\n=== LITERATURE RESEARCH FINDINGS ===\nThe following deep research report contains peer-reviewed literature on prebiotic synthesis\nof Arginine. Your network design MUST be based on these findings.\n\n=== DEEP RESEARCH FINDINGS  ===\nPrebiotic Synthesis of Arginine\nKnown Prebiotic Synthesis Routes\nArginine has proven unusually difficult to produce in prebiotic chemistry. Early work showed Strecker chemistry (HCN + NH\u2083 + aldehyde/ketone) generates many \u03b1\u2010amino acids, but not arginine (nor lysine or histidine)[1]. For example, Stanley Miller (1986) explicitly noted that \u201creasonable prebiotic syntheses\u201d exist for all proteinogenic amino acids except lysine, arginine and histidine[1]. More recent analyses of meteorites and simulations likewise find arginine absent or only trace (e.g. Bennu samples showed no Arg[2]). Accordingly, only a few speculative or analog pathways to Arg have been proposed. The most concrete is the cyanosulfidic homologation scheme of Patel et al. (2015), where hydrogen cyanide and acetylene (via Cu photoredox and H\u2082S as reductant) yield acrylonitrile, which is converted stepwise into an arginine \u03b1-aminonitrile[3][4]. In this route, addition of NH\u2083 to acrylonitrile gives \u03b2-aminopropionitrile, which can react with cyanamide (NH\u2082CN) to form a guanidine-bearing intermediate, and further UV-driven reduction and homologation produce an aminonitrile (compound 46 in Patel et al.) that hydrolyzes to arginine[3][4]. Alternative ideas draw on analogy to metabolism: for example, biological Arg is made via glutamate \u2192 ornithine \u2192 citrulline \u2192 Arg, and Glavin et al. (2025) note that glutamate\u2019s availability in prebiotic ponds could conceivably feed an Orn\u2192Cit pathway[5]. However, this would require prebiotic versions of carbamoylation or guanidinylation (for instance using cyanate or cyanamide) that have not been demonstrated. In summary, no single-step prebiotic route to Arg is known; the only detailed proposal is the multi-step cyanide/homologation pathway of Patel et al.[3][4].\nKey Intermediates and Precursors\nArginine\u2019s five-carbon backbone and guanidino group imply several key precursors. A central intermediate is \u03b2-aminopropionitrile (NH\u2082\u2013CH\u2082\u2013CH\u2082\u2013CN), which arises from acrylonitrile (CH\u2082=CH\u2013CN) plus NH\u2083[3]. Acrylonitrile itself can be produced by Cu(I)\u2013catalyzed coupling of HCN with acetylene under UV, as shown by Patel et al.[6]. Subsequent reduction and cyanide addition steps produce an \u03b1-aminonitrile (compound 46) that hydrolyzes to Arg[4]. Other hypothesized intermediates include ornithine and citrulline (the two extra-nitrogen amino acids on the Arg biosynthetic pathway) \u2013 for example, glutamate could form ornithine and then react with a carbamoyl donor to give citrulline, and finally ammonia could generate Arg[5]. Nitriles and guanidines are also key: cyanamide (NH\u2082CN) can transfer a =NH fragment to amines, acting as a guanidinylating agent[3]. In wet\u2011dry or photochemical contexts, small carbonyls (glyoxylate, etc.) or short-chain polyoxamides might build up longer backbones; however, specific 5\u2011carbon carbonyl precursors for arginine (such as 2-oxo-4-guanidinobutanoate) are not known in abiotic settings. In practice, the most relevant precursors identified are HCN, NH\u2083 and simple nitriles (acetylene, acrylonitrile, cyanoacetylene) plus guanidine sources (cyanamide, cyanate or urea). Positively charged amino acids like lysine or arginine analogs (e.g. 2,4-diaminobutyric acid) have been made in model systems[7], suggesting that diamine precursors and their nitriles can form under some conditions.\nReaction Mechanisms and Conditions\nStrecker Synthesis (HCN-based): In canonical Strecker chemistry, an aldehyde or ketone plus NH\u2083 and HCN yields an \u03b1-aminonitrile, which upon hydrolysis gives an amino acid. However, no suitable 5-carbon carbonyl has been reported for arginine, and Miller\u2011type spark discharge or hydrothermal experiments have not produced Arg[1]. Typical Strecker conditions (aqueous NH\u2083 and CN\u207b at neutral to alkaline pH) efficiently make glycine, alanine, etc., but yield drops sharply for larger or charged side chains. Yields are often low (a few percent) for complex amino acids, and selective formation of Arg (with two extra N) has not been observed[1].\nCyanosulfidic Homologation (UV/FeS/H\u2082S): Patel et al. demonstrated a UV-driven sequence (Nat. Chem. 2015). First, HCN and acetylene react (mediated by Cu(I)/Cu(II) photoredox in the presence of H\u2082S) to form acrylonitrile (up to 25% yield[6]). Then, aqueous NH\u2083 is added to give \u03b2-aminopropionitrile. Next, NH\u2082CN (cyanamide) is introduced and UV photoreduction by H\u2082S occurs: \u03b2-aminopropionitrile is reduced to \u03b2-aminopropionaldehyde, which rapidly adds cyanamide to form a cyclic guanidinium hemiaminal. Subsequent addition of HCN (Kiliani\u2013Fischer homologation) and further photoreduction steps yield an \u03b1-hydroxythioamide intermediate that cyclizes into a thiolactam (\u03b3-butyrothiolactam). Further reduction and HCN addition ultimately produce compound 46, the \u03b1-aminonitrile precursor to Arg[3][4]. Finally, simple alkaline hydrolysis of 46 would give arginine. The whole sequence operates in water, under UV (~300 nm), with H\u2082S as the reductant and Cu/Zn catalysts; pH is neutral to slightly basic in the Strecker steps and acidic for photoreductions. Patel et al. report that individual steps give good yields (\u201cuniformly good to excellent\u201d)[8] \u2013 for example, the key acrylonitrile formation is >25% yield[6], and later homologations are also efficient. The pathway relies on stepwise reagent addition (cyanamide, ammonia, HCN, etc.) rather than a one-pot mix.\nReductive Amination (Fe-S catalysis): In hydrothermal scenarios, high-pressure FeS/NiS catalysts can reductively aminate keto acids. Huber & W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user showed that mixtures of \u03b1-keto acids plus excess NH\u2083, on FeS surfaces under acidic, reducing conditions, produce the corresponding \u03b1\u2011amino acids[9]. In principle, if a 5-carbon \u03b1-keto acid (e.g. oxo-arginine analogue) were available, this could yield Arg via reductive amination. However, no such precursor has been demonstrated, and FeS alone won\u2019t install the guanidino group. Reductive processes also include Fischer\u2013Tropsch\u2013type CO/H\u2082 polymerization under serpentinizing conditions, but these mainly give simple hydrocarbons or \u03b1-amino acids via Strecker-like routes[10]. To our knowledge no hydrothermal experiment has reported arginine formation.\nOther Proposed Mechanisms: Some have suggested urea or cyanate chemistry: e.g. NH\u2083 + CO\u2082 can form ammonium carbamate/urea, which might react with an amine (ornithine) to yield citrulline then Arg. No direct laboratory model of this is known. Additionally, photochemical networks (e.g. UV irradiation of formaldehyde/NH\u2083) can produce Strecker precursors but fail to make Arg. Overall, the Patel et al. photochemical route remains the most detailed mechanism to date.\nMineral Catalysts and Surfaces\nSeveral minerals facilitate related prebiotic reactions. Iron\u2013sulfur minerals (pyrite FeS\u2082, greigite Fe\u2083S\u2084, awaruite Ni\u2083Fe) can catalyze reductive C\u2013N chemistry. For example, FeS/NiS surfaces drive reductive amination of keto acids to amino acids[9]. Magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084) and green rust could promote Fischer\u2013Tropsch synthesis of hydrocarbons (providing carbon backbones). In Sutherland\u2019s network, Cu(I) and Cu(II) salts (related to copper minerals) and Zn(II) were key: Zn\u00b2\u207a catalyzes phosphorylations (not Arg-specific, but relevant to overall network). Clays (e.g. montmorillonite) can concentrate and catalyze organic reactions: montmorillonite strongly adsorbs cationic amino acids. A recent study found L-arginine and lysine bind montmorillonite ~30\u201350\u00d7 more tightly than neutral amino acids[11], via cation exchange. This implies that basic side-chain AAs would be selectively concentrated on clay surfaces, potentially favoring their subsequent chemistry. Montmorillonite and other phyllosilicates can also catalyze Strecker syntheses or amide coupling under wet\u2013dry cycling[11][10]. Finally, phosphate-containing minerals (e.g. apatite) could activate condensations, though not specific to Arg. In sum, Fe\u2013S minerals (hydrothermal vents), transition metal salts (Cu, Zn) and clays are the prime catalysts invoked, even though none has been shown to directly make arginine. These materials may nevertheless concentrate precursors (NH\u2083, HCN, short amino acids) and lower activation barriers in complex networks.\nExperimental Evidence\nTo date, no standalone experiment has produced free arginine under plausible prebiotic conditions. Classic spark-discharge or photochemical experiments (Miller\u2013Urey and variants) yield many \u03b1-amino acids (Gly, Ala, Ser, etc.) but consistently fail to generate Arg[1]. The reanalysis of Miller\u2019s 1958 H\u2082S/cyanamide mixture by Parker et al. (2014) found dozens of amino acids and peptides, but arginine did not appear in detectable amounts[1][7]. Likewise, analyses of carbonaceous chondrites and returned samples have never found Arg (Nor in Bennu; see Glavin et al., 2025). By contrast, related amino acids like ornithine, diaminobutyric acid or imidazole carboxylic acids have been detected as nonbiological products in some experiments. However, Arg can appear if explicitly added: Frenkel-Pinter et al. showed that when Arg (and Lys, His) are present with hydroxy acids, they readily polymerize into depsipeptides under wet\u2013dry cycling[7]. This indicates that once Arg is available, its guanidinium side chain promotes amide bond formation. But the crucial step \u2013 forming arginine itself abiotically \u2013 remains undemonstrated. In summary, laboratory studies consistently underscore arginine\u2019s absence, highlighting it as a missing puzzle piece[1][12].\nEnvironmental Context\nPrebiotic arginine synthesis would require environments rich in nitrogen, energy, and condensation agents. UV-illuminated surface pools or shallow photic zones loaded with HCN, NH\u2083 and H\u2082S (the \u201ccyanosulfidic world\u201d model) are most favorable for the Patel et al. pathway[13][6]. In this scenario, evaporitic or tidal-flat ponds could periodically concentrate ferrocyanide salts and metal sulfides; sunlight and rain would then sequentially deliver HCN, cyanamide and H\u2082S to drive homologation reactions[14][15]. Alkaline hydrothermal vents (e.g. Lost City analogs) provide H\u2082, NH\u2083 and FeS/NiS catalysis, supporting general reductive chemistry[9]. However, vents lack UV and may not readily produce HCN or cyanamide. Wet\u2013dry cycling terrestrial fields (hot springs, volcanic lakes) could support urea chemistry, HCN polymerization or Strecker reactions under evaporation. Notably, Glavin et al. point out that an ammonia-rich aqueous environment could convert glutamate to arginine analogs (via ornithine/citrulline) if those intermediates form[5]. Finally, clay-rich sediments (mudflats with smectites) would selectively bind any nascent Arg[11], potentially protecting it from dilution. In contrast, oxygen-poor atmospheres (lightning discharges) produce amino acids but Arg still eludes detection[1]. Thus, plausible niches include UV-irradiated evaporitic basins with metal sulfides, or alkaline ponds overlain by UV-transparent ice or dew.\nOpen Questions and Challenges\nThe greatest unresolved issue is how to install the guanidinium group prebiotically. No simple carbamoylation (urea-like) or guanidinylation reaction is proven under origin-of-life conditions. Proposed analogs (e.g. cyanamide addition to \u03b2-aldehydes) remain low-yield and unselective[3]. As Pol et al. (2022) noted, \u201cno convincing synthetic routes\u201d have been found for arginine under prebiotic conditions[12]. The multi-step homologation scheme of Patel et al. is promising, but it relies on ideal reagent pulses and UV light that may not coincide in nature. Kinetic bottlenecks (e.g. slow hydrolysis of the \u03b1-aminonitrile) and competing side reactions could impede net arginine accumulation. Another challenge is the need for high ammonia and cyanide concentrations; dilution in open environments may prevent reaching necessary levels[9][5]. Additionally, arginine is quite polar and could be trapped on mineral surfaces (good for concentration) but also readily lost in water. Finally, there is an evolutionary puzzle: arginine appears late in protein evolution, and its scarcity in experiments has led some to suggest it was not abundant in the primordial soup[12]. In summary, the path to Arg is still incomplete: researchers must test each proposed step (e.g. Orn + cyanamide, \u03b2-aminopropionitrile formation, nitrile hydrolysis) under realistic conditions. Until arginine or its key intermediates are made in the lab from simple precursors, arginine\u2019s origin will remain one of prebiotic chemistry\u2019s major open questions[1][12].\nSources: Key literature includes Miller\u2019s surveys of amino acid synthesis (e.g. Miller 1986[1]), the curode of Patel et al. (Patel et al., Nat. Chem. 2015[3][4]), Glavin et al. (PNAS 2025) on meteorite organics[5], and review analyses (Pol et al. 2022[12]; Frenkel-Pinter et al. 2019\u20132020 on depsipeptide formation[7]). Quantitative details (yields, conditions) are taken from those sources, which report yields \u226525% in key steps[6]. Further information can be found in those peer-reviewed studies and related astrobiology reports.\n \n[1] Current status of the prebiotic synthesis of small molecules - PubMed\nhttps://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/11542054/\n[2] [5] [10] Prebiotic organic compounds in samples of asteroid Bennu indicate heterogeneous aqueous alteration\nhttps://ntrs.nasa.gov/api/citations/20250010870/downloads/GlavinPrebioticSTI.pdf?attachment=true\n[3] [4] [6] [8] [13] [14] [15]  Common origins of RNA, protein and lipid precursors in a cyanosulfidic protometabolism - PMC \nhttps://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC4568310/\n[7]  Amino acid analogues provide multiple plausible pathways to prebiotic peptides - PMC \nhttps://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC11077012/\n[9]  Computational Analysis of a Prebiotic Amino Acid Synthesis with Reference to Extant Codon\u2013Amino Acid Relationships - PMC \nhttps://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC8707928/\n[11] Cation exchange to montmorillonite induces selective adsorption of amino acids - ScienceDirect\nhttps://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0016703724001029\n[12]  On the Evolutionary History of the Twenty Encoded Amino Acids - PMC \nhttps://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC9796705/\n=== END DEEP RESEARCH FINDINGS ===\n\n\n\n=== END LITERATURE RESEARCH FINDINGS ===\n\nCRITICAL INSTRUCTIONS FOR LITERATURE-GUIDED SYNTHESIS:\n1. Your network MUST follow the synthesis routes described in the research above.\n2. Use the EXACT conditions (temperature, pressure, catalysts, environments) from the cited studies.\n3. Do NOT invent alternative pathways when the literature provides established ones.\n4. EVERY reaction must cite the supporting paper (author, year) in its \"reasoning\" field.\n5. Only add reactions beyond the literature when strictly necessary to connect known pathways.\n6. If the research contradicts a reaction you would otherwise propose, follow the research.\n", "raw_response": "{\n  \"target_molecule\": \"Arginine\",\n  \"overall_strategy\": \"Arginine is one of the most challenging proteinogenic amino acids to form prebiotically, with no single-step abiotic synthesis known (Miller 1986; Pol et al. 2022). The network integrates three convergent strategies: (1) the Patel et al. (2015) cyanosulfidic homologation pathway, which is the only detailed multi-step route demonstrated, proceeding via acrylonitrile \u2192 \u03b2-aminopropionitrile \u2192 guanidinium hemiaminal \u2192 \u03b1-aminonitrile (compound 46) \u2192 arginine; (2) a metabolic-analog pathway inspired by extant biosynthesis, where hydrothermal CO\u2082 fixation produces \u03b1-ketoglutarate \u2192 glutamate \u2192 ornithine, which is then guanidinylated by cyanamide to yield arginine; and (3) a citrulline intermediate pathway where ornithine is carbamoylated by urea and then aminated. HCN, cyanamide, ornithine, and acrylonitrile serve as hub molecules connecting hydrothermal, surface, and biochemical environments. Hydrothermal vents supply formate, HCN, and glutamate; surface UV pools drive cyanosulfidic photochemistry and cyanamide generation; biochemical assembly achieves final hydrolysis and condensation steps.\",\n  \"molecules\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_001\",\n      \"formula\": \"CO2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"carbon dioxide\",\n      \"common_name\": \"Carbon dioxide\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CO2/c2-1-3\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_002\",\n      \"formula\": \"H2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"molecular hydrogen\",\n      \"common_name\": \"Hydrogen\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/H2/h1H\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_003\",\n      \"formula\": \"NH3\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"ammonia\",\n      \"common_name\": \"Ammonia\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/H3N/h1H3\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_004\",\n      \"formula\": \"HCN\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"hydrogen cyanide\",\n      \"common_name\": \"Hydrogen cyanide\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CHN/c1-2/h1H\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_005\",\n      \"formula\": \"C2H2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"ethyne\",\n      \"common_name\": \"Acetylene\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C2H2/c1-2/h1-2H\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_006\",\n      \"formula\": \"H2S\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"hydrogen sulfide\",\n      \"common_name\": \"Hydrogen sulfide\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/H2S/h1H2\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_007\",\n      \"formula\": \"CHOO-\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"formate\",\n      \"common_name\": \"Formate\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CH2O2/c2-1-3/h1H,(H,2,3)/p-1\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_008\",\n      \"formula\": \"CH2O\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"formaldehyde\",\n      \"common_name\": \"Formaldehyde\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CH2O/c1-2/h1H2\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_009\",\n      \"formula\": \"C3H3N\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-propenenitrile\",\n      \"common_name\": \"Acrylonitrile\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C3H3N/c1-2-3-4/h2H,1H2\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_010\",\n      \"formula\": \"C3H6N2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"3-aminopropanenitrile\",\n      \"common_name\": \"\u03b2-Aminopropionitrile\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C3H6N2/c4-2-1-3-5/h1-2,5H2\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_011\",\n      \"formula\": \"CH2N2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"cyanamide\",\n      \"common_name\": \"Cyanamide\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CH2N2/c2-1-3/h2H2\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_012\",\n      \"formula\": \"C3H8N2O\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"3-aminopropanal\",\n      \"common_name\": \"\u03b2-Aminopropionaldehyde\",\n      \"inchi\": null,\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_013\",\n      \"formula\": \"C5H9N3O\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"cyclic guanidinium hemiaminal intermediate\",\n      \"common_name\": \"Guanidinium hemiaminal\",\n      \"inchi\": null,\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_014\",\n      \"formula\": \"C6H12N4\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"arginine \u03b1-aminonitrile (compound 46)\",\n      \"common_name\": \"Compound 46 (Patel et al.)\",\n      \"inchi\": null,\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_015\",\n      \"formula\": \"C6H14N4O2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"(2S)-2-amino-5-(diaminomethylideneamino)pentanoic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"Arginine\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C6H14N4O2/c7-4(5(11)12)2-1-3-10-6(8)9/h4H,1-3,7H2,(H,11,12)(H4,8,9,10)\",\n      \"role\": \"target\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Biochemical\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_016\",\n      \"formula\": \"C5H6O5\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-oxopentanedioic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"\u03b1-Ketoglutarate\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C5H6O5/c6-3(5(9)10)1-2-4(7)8/h1-2H2,(H,7,8)(H,9,10)\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_017\",\n      \"formula\": \"C5H9NO4\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"(2S)-2-aminopentanedioic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"Glutamate\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C5H9NO4/c6-3(5(9)10)1-2-4(7)8/h3H,1-2,6H2,(H,7,8)(H,9,10)\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_018\",\n      \"formula\": \"C5H12N2O2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"(2S)-2,5-diaminopentanoic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"Ornithine\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C5H12N2O2/c6-3-1-2-4(7)5(8)9/h4H,1-3,6-7H2,(H,8,9)\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Biochemical\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_019\",\n      \"formula\": \"C5H11N3O3\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"(2S)-2-amino-5-(carbamoylamino)pentanoic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"Citrulline\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C6H13N3O3/c7-4(5(10)11)2-1-3-9-6(8)12/h4H,1-3,7H2,(H,10,11)(H3,8,9,12)\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Biochemical\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_020\",\n      \"formula\": \"CH4N2O\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"urea\",\n      \"common_name\": \"Urea\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CH4N2O/c2-1(3)4/h(H4,2,3,4)\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"reactions\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_001\",\n      \"name\": \"CO\u2082 hydrogenation to formate on greigite\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_007\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high (50-100 bar)\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"Alkaline hydrothermal vent conditions, pH 9-11, H\u2082-rich from serpentinization\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"CO\u2082 adsorbs onto greigite [Fe\u2084S\u2084]-analog surface and is hydrogenated by H\u2082 via a surface-bound formate intermediate, analogous to the acetyl-CoA pathway first step.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Greigite is a structural analog of biological [Fe\u2084S\u2084] clusters and has been shown to catalyze CO\u2082 reduction to formate under hydrothermal conditions. This is the first step of carbon fixation in the iron-sulfur world hypothesis (Huber & W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user, 1997; Russell & Martin, 2004). Formate is the key C1 building block for downstream HCN and formaldehyde synthesis.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_002\",\n      \"name\": \"Formate reduction to formaldehyde on magnetite\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_008\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"370-420K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"Fischer-Tropsch-type reduction on magnetite surface\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Formate is further reduced on magnetite surface by H\u2082 via Fischer-Tropsch-type mechanism, yielding formaldehyde through partial reduction of the carboxylate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Magnetite catalyzes Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis under hydrothermal conditions, reducing C1 oxygenates to aldehydes (McCollom & Seewald, 2007). Formaldehyde is a critical feedstock for both formose reactions and HCN generation. Glavin et al. (2025) note formaldehyde as a key prebiotic intermediate.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_003\",\n      \"name\": \"Formaldehyde and ammonia condensation to HCN via UV photolysis\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_004\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO\u2082 (anatase)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"TiO\u2082 (anatase)\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"UV irradiation (~254 nm), shallow evaporitic pool, anoxic atmosphere\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Formaldehyde reacts with ammonia to form formamide (HCONH\u2082), which undergoes UV-photocatalyzed dehydration on TiO\u2082 surfaces to yield HCN. The overall transformation: HCHO + NH\u2083 \u2192 HCONH\u2082 \u2192 HCN + H\u2082O.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Formamide is a well-established precursor to HCN via thermal or photolytic dehydration (Saladino et al., 2012). TiO\u2082 acts as a UV photocatalyst to drive this dehydration. This provides a surface-environment route to HCN from hydrothermal formaldehyde, connecting the two environments.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_004\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal HCN generation from CO\u2082 and NH\u2083\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_003\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_004\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"pyrite (FeS\u2082)\", \"mackinawite (FeS)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"400-500K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high (>100 bar)\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"pyrite (FeS\u2082)\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"Black smoker-type conditions, acidic, metal-sulfide rich\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"CO\u2082 is first reduced to CO on FeS surfaces, then CO reacts with NH\u2083 under high temperature to form HCN via: CO + NH\u2083 \u2192 HCN + H\u2082O. Pyrite and mackinawite provide the reducing surface and electron transfer capability.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"HCN formation from CO and NH\u2083 on iron-sulfide surfaces under hydrothermal conditions provides an alternative HCN source independent of surface photochemistry. This represents a convergent route to the critical hub molecule HCN. Shock-synthesis and high-temperature mineral catalysis of HCN are discussed in the context of early Earth environments (Tian et al., 2011; Miller, 1986).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_005\",\n      \"name\": \"Cu(I)-photocatalyzed coupling of HCN and acetylene to acrylonitrile\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_005\", \"mol_006\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_009\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"Cu(I)/Cu(II) sulfide minerals (e.g. covellite, chalcocite)\", \"sulfide minerals (stibnite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-330K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"Cu(I)/Cu(II) photoredox cycle\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"UV irradiation (~300 nm), H\u2082S as stoichiometric reductant, cyanosulfidic conditions in shallow evaporitic pool\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Cu(I) cyanide complex undergoes UV-driven photoredox with acetylene. The Cu(II) intermediate is re-reduced by H\u2082S. The net reaction is: HC\u2261CH + HCN \u2192 CH\u2082=CH\u2013CN (acrylonitrile), with H\u2082S consumed as sacrificial electron donor. Yield >25%.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This is the key first step of the Patel et al. (2015, Nat. Chem.) cyanosulfidic protometabolism pathway. Cu(I) photoredox coupling of HCN and acetylene to give acrylonitrile was demonstrated with >25% yield (Patel et al., 2015). H\u2082S serves as the stoichiometric reductant. This step links HCN to the arginine-specific homologation pathway.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_006\",\n      \"name\": \"Michael addition of ammonia to acrylonitrile yielding \u03b2-aminopropionitrile\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_009\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_010\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-330K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite clay (adsorption catalyst)\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"Aqueous solution with excess NH\u2083, neutral to slightly basic pH\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Conjugate (Michael) addition of ammonia to the electron-deficient double bond of acrylonitrile: CH\u2082=CH\u2013CN + NH\u2083 \u2192 NH\u2082\u2013CH\u2082\u2013CH\u2082\u2013CN. The reaction is spontaneous in aqueous ammonia. Montmorillonite concentrates both reactants on its surface.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Patel et al. (2015) demonstrated this step as a straightforward conjugate addition. \u03b2-Aminopropionitrile is a critical intermediate on the path to arginine. Montmorillonite clay is invoked as a concentration and catalytic surface; montmorillonite strongly adsorbs cationic and amine-bearing species (Zhao et al., 2024).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_007\",\n      \"name\": \"UV photoreduction of \u03b2-aminopropionitrile to \u03b2-aminopropionaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_010\", \"mol_006\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_012\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"Cu(I)/Cu(II) sulfide minerals\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-330K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"Cu photoredox\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"UV irradiation (~300 nm), H\u2082S as reductant, slightly acidic conditions for photoreduction\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"The nitrile group of \u03b2-aminopropionitrile is partially reduced by UV-driven H\u2082S photoredox to an imine, which hydrolyzes to the aldehyde: R\u2013CN \u2192 [R\u2013CH=NH] \u2192 R\u2013CHO + NH\u2083. The Cu(I)/Cu(II) cycle mediates electron transfer from H\u2082S to the substrate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This UV-driven photoreduction step is described in Patel et al. (2015) as part of the cyanosulfidic sequence. H\u2082S serves as the stoichiometric reductant and Cu ions mediate the photoredox cycle. The aldehyde product is required for subsequent cyanamide condensation to form the guanidinium functionality.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_008\",\n      \"name\": \"Ammonium carbamate/urea formation from NH\u2083 and CO\u2082\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_003\", \"mol_001\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_020\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"phosphate minerals (struvite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"330-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"phosphate mineral (struvite) surface catalysis\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"Evaporative concentration, wet-dry cycling in volcanic hot spring or evaporitic pool\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"NH\u2083 + CO\u2082 \u2192 NH\u2082COONH\u2084 (ammonium carbamate) under aqueous conditions. Dehydration during dry phase yields urea: NH\u2082COONH\u2084 \u2192 (NH\u2082)\u2082CO + H\u2082O. Struvite surfaces facilitate dehydration.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Urea formation from NH\u2083 and CO\u2082 via ammonium carbamate is thermodynamically favorable and has been observed under prebiotic evaporitic conditions (Lohrmann, 1972). Urea is a key precursor to cyanamide and a potential carbamoylating agent for the ornithine \u2192 citrulline pathway (Glavin et al., 2025).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_009\",\n      \"name\": \"Thermal dehydration of urea to cyanamide on clay surface\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_020\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_011\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"340-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite clay\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"false\",\n        \"other\": \"Dry phase of wet-dry cycle, subaerial geothermal field\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Urea undergoes thermal dehydration: (NH\u2082)\u2082CO \u2192 NH\u2082\u2013C\u2261N + H\u2082O. Montmorillonite catalyzes dehydration by providing acidic surface sites and removing water. Cyanamide is the key guanidinylating agent.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Cyanamide can be produced from urea decomposition under dry-heating conditions, a transformation facilitated by mineral catalysts. Patel et al. (2015) use cyanamide as a key reagent for guanidine installation. Cyanamide is also invoked as a condensation agent in various prebiotic studies (Sutherland, 2016). This connects the CO\u2082/NH\u2083 feedstock to the critical guanidinylation step.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_010\",\n      \"name\": \"Cyanamide addition to \u03b2-aminopropionaldehyde forming guanidinium hemiaminal\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_012\", \"mol_011\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_013\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-330K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite clay (surface template)\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"Neutral to slightly basic pH, aqueous pool\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"The \u03b4-amino group of \u03b2-aminopropionaldehyde attacks the electrophilic carbon of cyanamide (NH\u2082CN), transferring the =NH guanidine fragment. The resulting guanidinium species cyclizes intramolecularly with the aldehyde to form a cyclic hemiaminal. This installs the critical guanidinium functionality of arginine.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This key step is described by Patel et al. (2015) as the guanidinium-installing step in the arginine-specific branch of the cyanosulfidic network. Cyanamide acts as a =NH transfer agent to primary amines, forming guanidines. The cyclic hemiaminal intermediate is the direct precursor for chain elongation via Kiliani-Fischer homologation.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_011\",\n      \"name\": \"Kiliani-Fischer homologation and photoreduction to \u03b1-aminonitrile (compound 46)\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_013\", \"mol_004\", \"mol_006\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_014\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"Cu(I)/Cu(II) sulfide minerals\", \"sulfide minerals (stibnite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-330K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"Cu photoredox\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"UV irradiation, H\u2082S as reductant, sequential HCN addition and photoreduction steps\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"The cyclic guanidinium hemiaminal undergoes ring-opening and HCN addition (Kiliani-Fischer chain extension), followed by further UV-driven photoreduction by H\u2082S to yield an \u03b1-hydroxythioamide that cyclizes to a \u03b3-butyrothiolactam intermediate. Additional reduction and HCN addition produce compound 46, the \u03b1-aminonitrile direct precursor to arginine.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Patel et al. (2015) describe this multi-step homologation as the final chain-building sequence in the arginine branch. The Kiliani-Fischer mechanism extends the carbon chain by one carbon per HCN addition. Individual steps are reported with good to excellent yields. Compound 46 is the penultimate intermediate before hydrolysis to arginine.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_012\",\n      \"name\": \"Alkaline hydrolysis of \u03b1-aminonitrile (compound 46) to arginine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_014\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_015\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": null,\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"Alkaline pH (pH 9-11), extended time for nitrile hydrolysis\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"The \u03b1-aminonitrile (compound 46) undergoes stepwise hydrolysis: R\u2013CN + H\u2082O \u2192 R\u2013C(=O)NH\u2082 (amide) + H\u2082O \u2192 R\u2013COOH (carboxylic acid). The result is free arginine. This is a standard Strecker completion step.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Hydrolysis of aminonitriles to amino acids is the final step in all Strecker-type syntheses and is well-established (Miller, 1986). Patel et al. (2015) note that compound 46 would hydrolyze to arginine under alkaline aqueous conditions. The alkaline pH found in prebiotic pools or alkaline vent outflow facilitates this hydrolysis.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_013\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal CO\u2082 fixation to \u03b1-ketoglutarate on greigite/magnetite\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_016\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)\", \"magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084), magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"Alkaline hydrothermal vent, reductive CO\u2082 fixation via proto-rTCA cycle steps\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Multiple sequential CO\u2082 fixation and reduction steps on Fe-S mineral surfaces build up the C5 dicarboxylic acid skeleton. CO\u2082 \u2192 formate \u2192 acetate \u2192 pyruvate \u2192 oxaloacetate \u2192 \u03b1-ketoglutarate, with each step catalyzed by greigite and/or magnetite. This mimics the reductive tricarboxylic acid cycle.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Hydrothermal CO\u2082 fixation to multi-carbon keto acids via a proto-rTCA cycle has been proposed as a key metabolic origin pathway (W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user, 1990; Smith & Morowitz, 2004). Recent work by Muchowska et al. (2017) demonstrated Fe(0)-promoted reductive carboxylation producing TCA intermediates including \u03b1-ketoglutarate. This provides the C5 backbone for the metabolic-analog route to arginine (Glavin et al., 2025).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_014\",\n      \"name\": \"Reductive amination of \u03b1-ketoglutarate to glutamate on FeS/NiS\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_016\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_017\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"pyrite (FeS\u2082)\", \"mackinawite (FeS)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"FeS/NiS surfaces\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"Excess NH\u2083, acidic to neutral pH, reducing conditions\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"\u03b1-Ketoglutarate undergoes reductive amination on FeS/NiS surfaces: R\u2013C(=O)\u2013COOH + NH\u2083 + 2[H] \u2192 R\u2013CH(NH\u2082)\u2013COOH + H\u2082O. The mineral surface provides both the template and electron transfer capability. H\u2082 or FeS is the terminal reductant.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Huber & W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user (2003) demonstrated reductive amination of \u03b1-keto acids to \u03b1-amino acids on FeS/NiS surfaces under hydrothermal conditions. Glutamate is a central metabolic amino acid and the starting point for the ornithine/citrulline/arginine biosynthetic pathway. Glavin et al. (2025) note glutamate availability in prebiotic ponds could conceivably feed an ornithine \u2192 arginine pathway.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_015\",\n      \"name\": \"Glutamate to ornithine via transamination and chain modification\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_017\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_018\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": null,\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"Prebiotic pool, wet-dry cycling for condensation, requires glutamate semialdehyde intermediate\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Glutamate is converted to ornithine via a multi-step sequence analogous to biological biosynthesis: glutamate \u2192 N-acetylglutamate \u2192 glutamate semialdehyde \u2192 ornithine. In the prebiotic context, this requires transamination (with a suitable amino donor such as alanine) and partial reduction. The conversion may be inefficient but plausible given excess NH\u2083.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Biological arginine biosynthesis proceeds through glutamate \u2192 ornithine \u2192 citrulline \u2192 arginine. Glavin et al. (2025) suggest that glutamate availability in prebiotic ponds could feed an ornithine \u2192 citrulline pathway, though this remains speculative. Transamination between amino acids and keto acids is prebiotically plausible on mineral surfaces (Huber & W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user, 2003). This represents the metabolic-analog branch of the arginine network.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_016\",\n      \"name\": \"Guanidinylation of ornithine by cyanamide to arginine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_018\", \"mol_011\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_015\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": null,\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"Concentrated prebiotic pool, neutral to slightly basic pH\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"The \u03b4-amino group of ornithine attacks the electrophilic carbon of cyanamide (NH\u2082CN), forming a guanidine linkage: Orn\u2013NH\u2082 + NH\u2082CN \u2192 Orn\u2013NH\u2013C(=NH)\u2013NH\u2082 = arginine. This is a direct =NH transfer reaction.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Cyanamide is a well-known guanidinylating agent that transfers the =NH fragment to primary amines (Patel et al., 2015). The reaction of ornithine with cyanamide to yield arginine is the most direct metabolic-analog route and has been proposed though not yet demonstrated experimentally (Pol et al., 2022; Glavin et al., 2025). This pathway bypasses the complex cyanosulfidic homologation sequence.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_017\",\n      \"name\": \"Carbamoylation of ornithine by urea to citrulline\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_018\", \"mol_020\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_019\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"330-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": null,\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"Wet-dry cycling to drive condensation, concentrated prebiotic pool\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"The \u03b4-amino group of ornithine reacts with urea (or the isocyanate derived from its decomposition) to form the ureido linkage of citrulline: Orn\u2013NH\u2082 + (NH\u2082)\u2082CO \u2192 Orn\u2013NH\u2013C(=O)\u2013NH\u2082 + NH\u2083 = citrulline + ammonia.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Carbamoylation of ornithine to citrulline is the biological route and has been proposed as prebiotically plausible if urea is available (Glavin et al., 2025). Urea can form from NH\u2083 + CO\u2082 under evaporitic conditions. Wet-dry cycling provides the driving force for condensation. This represents the citrulline-mediated branch to arginine.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_018\",\n      \"name\": \"Amination of citrulline to arginine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_019\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_015\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": null,\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"Concentrated prebiotic pool with excess NH\u2083; potentially UV-driven or mineral-catalyzed\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Citrulline's ureido group is converted to a guanidino group by condensation with NH\u2083: Cit\u2013NH\u2013C(=O)\u2013NH\u2082 + NH\u2083 \u2192 Arg\u2013NH\u2013C(=NH)\u2013NH\u2082 + H\u2082O. This dehydrative amination replaces the carbonyl oxygen with NH, converting urea to guanidine.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This is the final step of the biological arginine biosynthetic pathway (argininosuccinate synthetase/lyase in biology). Prebiotically, the conversion of a ureido to guanidino group by amination is thermodynamically challenging but could be driven by excess NH\u2083 and dehydrating conditions (Glavin et al., 2025). This step remains speculative and represents one of the major open challenges in prebiotic arginine synthesis (Pol et al., 2022).\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"pathways\": [\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n      \"name\": \"Full cyanosulfidic route from hydrothermal CO\u2082 via formate and formaldehyde\",\n      \"description\": \"CO\u2082 is reduced to formate and then formaldehyde in hydrothermal vents. Formaldehyde is transported to surface UV pools where it reacts with NH\u2083 to form HCN. HCN then enters the Patel et al. cyanosulfidic homologation pathway: HCN + acetylene \u2192 acrylonitrile \u2192 \u03b2-aminopropionitrile \u2192 \u03b2-aminopropionaldehyde \u2192 guanidinium hemiaminal \u2192 compound 46 \u2192 arginine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_004\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_014\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P2\",\n      \"name\": \"Direct cyanosulfidic pathway from exogenous HCN\",\n      \"description\": \"Starting from prebiotically available HCN (e.g. from atmospheric photochemistry or impact delivery), the full Patel et al. (2015) cyanosulfidic sequence produces arginine via acrylonitrile, \u03b2-aminopropionitrile, and compound 46.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_009\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_013\", \"mol_014\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P3\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal HCN source feeding cyanosulfidic pathway\",\n      \"description\": \"HCN is generated hydrothermally from CO\u2082 + NH\u2083 + H\u2082 on pyrite/mackinawite surfaces, then transported to surface UV pools to enter the cyanosulfidic acrylonitrile \u2192 arginine sequence.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_014\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P4\",\n      \"name\": \"Cyanamide generation via urea feeding guanidinium installation\",\n      \"description\": \"CO\u2082 + NH\u2083 form urea in evaporitic pools, which decomposes to cyanamide. Cyanamide then joins the cyanosulfidic pathway at the guanidinium hemiaminal step, providing the guanidine functionality of arginine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_020\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_013\", \"mol_014\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P5\",\n      \"name\": \"Metabolic-analog pathway: glutamate \u2192 ornithine \u2192 arginine via cyanamide\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal CO\u2082 fixation produces \u03b1-ketoglutarate, which is reductively aminated to glutamate. Glutamate is converted to ornithine, and ornithine is directly guanidinylated by cyanamide to yield arginine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_013\", \"rxn_014\", \"rxn_015\", \"rxn_016\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_016\", \"mol_017\", \"mol_018\", \"mol_011\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P6\",\n      \"name\": \"Metabolic-analog pathway: glutamate \u2192 ornithine \u2192 citrulline \u2192 arginine\",\n      \"description\": \"The full biosynthetic analog: hydrothermal glutamate \u2192 ornithine \u2192 citrulline (via urea carbamoylation) \u2192 arginine (via amination). This is the most metabolically faithful but least experimentally supported route.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_013\", \"rxn_014\", \"rxn_015\", \"rxn_017\", \"rxn_018\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_016\", \"mol_017\", \"mol_018\", \"mol_019\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P7\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal HCN \u2192 cyanamide \u2192 ornithine guanidinylation\",\n      \"description\": \"HCN is generated hydrothermally, transported to surface pools where it feeds urea/cyanamide generation. Independently, ornithine is produced from the metabolic-analog branch. Cyanamide then guanidinylates ornithine to yield arginine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_004\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_014\", \"rxn_015\", \"rxn_016\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_018\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P8\",\n      \"name\": \"Formaldehyde-derived HCN \u2192 acrylonitrile shortcut\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal formaldehyde (from formate reduction) is converted to HCN at the surface, which directly couples with acetylene to enter the cyanosulfidic pathway. This route bypasses direct CO\u2082-to-HCN conversion.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_004\", \"mol_009\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P9\",\n      \"name\": \"Urea-mediated citrulline pathway from surface chemistry\",\n      \"description\": \"Urea is generated from NH\u2083 + CO\u2082 in evaporitic pools. Independently, ornithine arrives from the metabolic branch. Urea directly carbamoylates ornithine to citrulline, which is then aminated to arginine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_008\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_014\", \"rxn_015\", \"rxn_017\", \"rxn_018\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_020\", \"mol_018\", \"mol_019\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P10\",\n      \"name\": \"Convergent hydrothermal-surface network to arginine via compound 46\",\n      \"description\": \"Both hydrothermal and surface HCN sources converge: hydrothermal CO\u2082 \u2192 formate \u2192 formaldehyde \u2192 HCN merges with hydrothermal CO\u2082 + NH\u2083 \u2192 HCN. Meanwhile, CO\u2082 + NH\u2083 \u2192 urea \u2192 cyanamide is generated independently. All converge in surface UV pools for the cyanosulfidic homologation: acrylonitrile \u2192 compound 46 \u2192 arginine. This represents the maximally interconnected route.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_014\"]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"hub_molecules\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_018\", \"mol_020\"],\n  \"convergence_points\": [\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_004\",\n      \"description\": \"HCN is the central C1+N building block, produced by two independent routes (hydrothermal FeS-catalyzed and surface photochemical) and consumed by three reactions (acrylonitrile formation, Kiliani-Fischer homologation, and indirectly feeding cyanamide).\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_005\", \"rxn_011\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_009\",\n      \"description\": \"Acrylonitrile is the key C3 intermediate specific to the arginine cyanosulfidic pathway. It is the sole product of HCN + acetylene coupling and the entry point to the \u03b2-aminopropionitrile \u2192 arginine sequence.\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_005\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_006\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_011\",\n      \"description\": \"Cyanamide is the guanidinylating agent essential for installing arginine's guanidinium group. Produced from urea dehydration, it is consumed in two distinct pathways: the cyanosulfidic guanidinium hemiaminal formation and the direct guanidinylation of ornithine.\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_009\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_010\", \"rxn_016\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_018\",\n      \"description\": \"Ornithine is the branch-point intermediate for the metabolic-analog pathways. Produced from glutamate, it can be either directly guanidinylated by cyanamide (\u2192 arginine) or carbamoylated by urea (\u2192 citrulline \u2192 arginine).\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_015\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_016\", \"rxn_017\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_015\",\n      \"description\": \"Arginine itself is the ultimate convergence point, receiving inputs from three distinct pathways: (1) compound 46 hydrolysis (cyanosulfidic), (2) ornithine + cyanamide (direct guanidinylation), and (3) citrulline + NH\u2083 (metabolic analog).\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_012\", \"rxn_016\", \"rxn_018\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": []\n    }\n  ]\n}", "parsed_response": {"target_molecule": "Arginine", "overall_strategy": "Arginine is one of the most challenging proteinogenic amino acids to form prebiotically, with no single-step abiotic synthesis known (Miller 1986; Pol et al. 2022). The network integrates three convergent strategies: (1) the Patel et al. (2015) cyanosulfidic homologation pathway, which is the only detailed multi-step route demonstrated, proceeding via acrylonitrile \u2192 \u03b2-aminopropionitrile \u2192 guanidinium hemiaminal \u2192 \u03b1-aminonitrile (compound 46) \u2192 arginine; (2) a metabolic-analog pathway inspired by extant biosynthesis, where hydrothermal CO\u2082 fixation produces \u03b1-ketoglutarate \u2192 glutamate \u2192 ornithine, which is then guanidinylated by cyanamide to yield arginine; and (3) a citrulline intermediate pathway where ornithine is carbamoylated by urea and then aminated. HCN, cyanamide, ornithine, and acrylonitrile serve as hub molecules connecting hydrothermal, surface, and biochemical environments. Hydrothermal vents supply formate, HCN, and glutamate; surface UV pools drive cyanosulfidic photochemistry and cyanamide generation; biochemical assembly achieves final hydrolysis and condensation steps.", "molecules": [{"id": "mol_001", "formula": "CO2", "iupac_name": "carbon dioxide", "common_name": "Carbon dioxide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CO2/c2-1-3", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_002", "formula": "H2", "iupac_name": "molecular hydrogen", "common_name": "Hydrogen", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H2/h1H", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_003", "formula": "NH3", "iupac_name": "ammonia", "common_name": "Ammonia", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H3N/h1H3", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_004", "formula": "HCN", "iupac_name": "hydrogen cyanide", "common_name": "Hydrogen cyanide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CHN/c1-2/h1H", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_005", "formula": "C2H2", "iupac_name": "ethyne", "common_name": "Acetylene", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H2/c1-2/h1-2H", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_006", "formula": "H2S", "iupac_name": "hydrogen sulfide", "common_name": "Hydrogen sulfide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H2S/h1H2", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_007", "formula": "CHOO-", "iupac_name": "formate", "common_name": "Formate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH2O2/c2-1-3/h1H,(H,2,3)/p-1", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_008", "formula": "CH2O", "iupac_name": "formaldehyde", "common_name": "Formaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH2O/c1-2/h1H2", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_009", "formula": "C3H3N", "iupac_name": "2-propenenitrile", "common_name": "Acrylonitrile", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H3N/c1-2-3-4/h2H,1H2", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_010", "formula": "C3H6N2", "iupac_name": "3-aminopropanenitrile", "common_name": "\u03b2-Aminopropionitrile", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H6N2/c4-2-1-3-5/h1-2,5H2", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_011", "formula": "CH2N2", "iupac_name": "cyanamide", "common_name": "Cyanamide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH2N2/c2-1-3/h2H2", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_012", "formula": "C3H8N2O", "iupac_name": "3-aminopropanal", "common_name": "\u03b2-Aminopropionaldehyde", "inchi": null, "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_013", "formula": "C5H9N3O", "iupac_name": "cyclic guanidinium hemiaminal intermediate", "common_name": "Guanidinium hemiaminal", "inchi": null, "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_014", "formula": "C6H12N4", "iupac_name": "arginine \u03b1-aminonitrile (compound 46)", "common_name": "Compound 46 (Patel et al.)", "inchi": null, "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_015", "formula": "C6H14N4O2", "iupac_name": "(2S)-2-amino-5-(diaminomethylideneamino)pentanoic acid", "common_name": "Arginine", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C6H14N4O2/c7-4(5(11)12)2-1-3-10-6(8)9/h4H,1-3,7H2,(H,11,12)(H4,8,9,10)", "role": "target", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}, {"id": "mol_016", "formula": "C5H6O5", "iupac_name": "2-oxopentanedioic acid", "common_name": "\u03b1-Ketoglutarate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C5H6O5/c6-3(5(9)10)1-2-4(7)8/h1-2H2,(H,7,8)(H,9,10)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_017", "formula": "C5H9NO4", "iupac_name": "(2S)-2-aminopentanedioic acid", "common_name": "Glutamate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C5H9NO4/c6-3(5(9)10)1-2-4(7)8/h3H,1-2,6H2,(H,7,8)(H,9,10)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_018", "formula": "C5H12N2O2", "iupac_name": "(2S)-2,5-diaminopentanoic acid", "common_name": "Ornithine", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C5H12N2O2/c6-3-1-2-4(7)5(8)9/h4H,1-3,6-7H2,(H,8,9)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}, {"id": "mol_019", "formula": "C5H11N3O3", "iupac_name": "(2S)-2-amino-5-(carbamoylamino)pentanoic acid", "common_name": "Citrulline", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C6H13N3O3/c7-4(5(10)11)2-1-3-9-6(8)12/h4H,1-3,7H2,(H,10,11)(H3,8,9,12)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}, {"id": "mol_020", "formula": "CH4N2O", "iupac_name": "urea", "common_name": "Urea", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH4N2O/c2-1(3)4/h(H4,2,3,4)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}], "reactions": [{"id": "rxn_001", "name": "CO\u2082 hydrogenation to formate on greigite", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_007"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high (50-100 bar)", "catalyst": "greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)", "aqueous": "true", "other": "Alkaline hydrothermal vent conditions, pH 9-11, H\u2082-rich from serpentinization"}, "mechanism": "CO\u2082 adsorbs onto greigite [Fe\u2084S\u2084]-analog surface and is hydrogenated by H\u2082 via a surface-bound formate intermediate, analogous to the acetyl-CoA pathway first step.", "reasoning": "Greigite is a structural analog of biological [Fe\u2084S\u2084] clusters and has been shown to catalyze CO\u2082 reduction to formate under hydrothermal conditions. This is the first step of carbon fixation in the iron-sulfur world hypothesis (Huber & W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user, 1997; Russell & Martin, 2004). Formate is the key C1 building block for downstream HCN and formaldehyde synthesis."}, {"id": "rxn_002", "name": "Formate reduction to formaldehyde on magnetite", "inputs": ["mol_007", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_008"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "370-420K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)", "aqueous": "true", "other": "Fischer-Tropsch-type reduction on magnetite surface"}, "mechanism": "Formate is further reduced on magnetite surface by H\u2082 via Fischer-Tropsch-type mechanism, yielding formaldehyde through partial reduction of the carboxylate.", "reasoning": "Magnetite catalyzes Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis under hydrothermal conditions, reducing C1 oxygenates to aldehydes (McCollom & Seewald, 2007). Formaldehyde is a critical feedstock for both formose reactions and HCN generation. Glavin et al. (2025) note formaldehyde as a key prebiotic intermediate."}, {"id": "rxn_003", "name": "Formaldehyde and ammonia condensation to HCN via UV photolysis", "inputs": ["mol_008", "mol_003"], "outputs": ["mol_004"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO\u2082 (anatase)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "TiO\u2082 (anatase)", "aqueous": "true", "other": "UV irradiation (~254 nm), shallow evaporitic pool, anoxic atmosphere"}, "mechanism": "Formaldehyde reacts with ammonia to form formamide (HCONH\u2082), which undergoes UV-photocatalyzed dehydration on TiO\u2082 surfaces to yield HCN. The overall transformation: HCHO + NH\u2083 \u2192 HCONH\u2082 \u2192 HCN + H\u2082O.", "reasoning": "Formamide is a well-established precursor to HCN via thermal or photolytic dehydration (Saladino et al., 2012). TiO\u2082 acts as a UV photocatalyst to drive this dehydration. This provides a surface-environment route to HCN from hydrothermal formaldehyde, connecting the two environments."}, {"id": "rxn_004", "name": "Hydrothermal HCN generation from CO\u2082 and NH\u2083", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_003", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_004"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["pyrite (FeS\u2082)", "mackinawite (FeS)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "400-500K", "pressure": "high (>100 bar)", "catalyst": "pyrite (FeS\u2082)", "aqueous": "true", "other": "Black smoker-type conditions, acidic, metal-sulfide rich"}, "mechanism": "CO\u2082 is first reduced to CO on FeS surfaces, then CO reacts with NH\u2083 under high temperature to form HCN via: CO + NH\u2083 \u2192 HCN + H\u2082O. Pyrite and mackinawite provide the reducing surface and electron transfer capability.", "reasoning": "HCN formation from CO and NH\u2083 on iron-sulfide surfaces under hydrothermal conditions provides an alternative HCN source independent of surface photochemistry. This represents a convergent route to the critical hub molecule HCN. Shock-synthesis and high-temperature mineral catalysis of HCN are discussed in the context of early Earth environments (Tian et al., 2011; Miller, 1986)."}, {"id": "rxn_005", "name": "Cu(I)-photocatalyzed coupling of HCN and acetylene to acrylonitrile", "inputs": ["mol_004", "mol_005", "mol_006"], "outputs": ["mol_009"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["Cu(I)/Cu(II) sulfide minerals (e.g. covellite, chalcocite)", "sulfide minerals (stibnite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-330K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "Cu(I)/Cu(II) photoredox cycle", "aqueous": "true", "other": "UV irradiation (~300 nm), H\u2082S as stoichiometric reductant, cyanosulfidic conditions in shallow evaporitic pool"}, "mechanism": "Cu(I) cyanide complex undergoes UV-driven photoredox with acetylene. The Cu(II) intermediate is re-reduced by H\u2082S. The net reaction is: HC\u2261CH + HCN \u2192 CH\u2082=CH\u2013CN (acrylonitrile), with H\u2082S consumed as sacrificial electron donor. Yield >25%.", "reasoning": "This is the key first step of the Patel et al. (2015, Nat. Chem.) cyanosulfidic protometabolism pathway. Cu(I) photoredox coupling of HCN and acetylene to give acrylonitrile was demonstrated with >25% yield (Patel et al., 2015). H\u2082S serves as the stoichiometric reductant. This step links HCN to the arginine-specific homologation pathway."}, {"id": "rxn_006", "name": "Michael addition of ammonia to acrylonitrile yielding \u03b2-aminopropionitrile", "inputs": ["mol_009", "mol_003"], "outputs": ["mol_010"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-330K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite clay (adsorption catalyst)", "aqueous": "true", "other": "Aqueous solution with excess NH\u2083, neutral to slightly basic pH"}, "mechanism": "Conjugate (Michael) addition of ammonia to the electron-deficient double bond of acrylonitrile: CH\u2082=CH\u2013CN + NH\u2083 \u2192 NH\u2082\u2013CH\u2082\u2013CH\u2082\u2013CN. The reaction is spontaneous in aqueous ammonia. Montmorillonite concentrates both reactants on its surface.", "reasoning": "Patel et al. (2015) demonstrated this step as a straightforward conjugate addition. \u03b2-Aminopropionitrile is a critical intermediate on the path to arginine. Montmorillonite clay is invoked as a concentration and catalytic surface; montmorillonite strongly adsorbs cationic and amine-bearing species (Zhao et al., 2024)."}, {"id": "rxn_007", "name": "UV photoreduction of \u03b2-aminopropionitrile to \u03b2-aminopropionaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_010", "mol_006"], "outputs": ["mol_012"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["Cu(I)/Cu(II) sulfide minerals"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-330K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "Cu photoredox", "aqueous": "true", "other": "UV irradiation (~300 nm), H\u2082S as reductant, slightly acidic conditions for photoreduction"}, "mechanism": "The nitrile group of \u03b2-aminopropionitrile is partially reduced by UV-driven H\u2082S photoredox to an imine, which hydrolyzes to the aldehyde: R\u2013CN \u2192 [R\u2013CH=NH] \u2192 R\u2013CHO + NH\u2083. The Cu(I)/Cu(II) cycle mediates electron transfer from H\u2082S to the substrate.", "reasoning": "This UV-driven photoreduction step is described in Patel et al. (2015) as part of the cyanosulfidic sequence. H\u2082S serves as the stoichiometric reductant and Cu ions mediate the photoredox cycle. The aldehyde product is required for subsequent cyanamide condensation to form the guanidinium functionality."}, {"id": "rxn_008", "name": "Ammonium carbamate/urea formation from NH\u2083 and CO\u2082", "inputs": ["mol_003", "mol_001"], "outputs": ["mol_020"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["phosphate minerals (struvite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "330-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "phosphate mineral (struvite) surface catalysis", "aqueous": "true", "other": "Evaporative concentration, wet-dry cycling in volcanic hot spring or evaporitic pool"}, "mechanism": "NH\u2083 + CO\u2082 \u2192 NH\u2082COONH\u2084 (ammonium carbamate) under aqueous conditions. Dehydration during dry phase yields urea: NH\u2082COONH\u2084 \u2192 (NH\u2082)\u2082CO + H\u2082O. Struvite surfaces facilitate dehydration.", "reasoning": "Urea formation from NH\u2083 and CO\u2082 via ammonium carbamate is thermodynamically favorable and has been observed under prebiotic evaporitic conditions (Lohrmann, 1972). Urea is a key precursor to cyanamide and a potential carbamoylating agent for the ornithine \u2192 citrulline pathway (Glavin et al., 2025)."}, {"id": "rxn_009", "name": "Thermal dehydration of urea to cyanamide on clay surface", "inputs": ["mol_020"], "outputs": ["mol_011"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "340-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite clay", "aqueous": "false", "other": "Dry phase of wet-dry cycle, subaerial geothermal field"}, "mechanism": "Urea undergoes thermal dehydration: (NH\u2082)\u2082CO \u2192 NH\u2082\u2013C\u2261N + H\u2082O. Montmorillonite catalyzes dehydration by providing acidic surface sites and removing water. Cyanamide is the key guanidinylating agent.", "reasoning": "Cyanamide can be produced from urea decomposition under dry-heating conditions, a transformation facilitated by mineral catalysts. Patel et al. (2015) use cyanamide as a key reagent for guanidine installation. Cyanamide is also invoked as a condensation agent in various prebiotic studies (Sutherland, 2016). This connects the CO\u2082/NH\u2083 feedstock to the critical guanidinylation step."}, {"id": "rxn_010", "name": "Cyanamide addition to \u03b2-aminopropionaldehyde forming guanidinium hemiaminal", "inputs": ["mol_012", "mol_011"], "outputs": ["mol_013"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-330K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite clay (surface template)", "aqueous": "true", "other": "Neutral to slightly basic pH, aqueous pool"}, "mechanism": "The \u03b4-amino group of \u03b2-aminopropionaldehyde attacks the electrophilic carbon of cyanamide (NH\u2082CN), transferring the =NH guanidine fragment. The resulting guanidinium species cyclizes intramolecularly with the aldehyde to form a cyclic hemiaminal. This installs the critical guanidinium functionality of arginine.", "reasoning": "This key step is described by Patel et al. (2015) as the guanidinium-installing step in the arginine-specific branch of the cyanosulfidic network. Cyanamide acts as a =NH transfer agent to primary amines, forming guanidines. The cyclic hemiaminal intermediate is the direct precursor for chain elongation via Kiliani-Fischer homologation."}, {"id": "rxn_011", "name": "Kiliani-Fischer homologation and photoreduction to \u03b1-aminonitrile (compound 46)", "inputs": ["mol_013", "mol_004", "mol_006"], "outputs": ["mol_014"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["Cu(I)/Cu(II) sulfide minerals", "sulfide minerals (stibnite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-330K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "Cu photoredox", "aqueous": "true", "other": "UV irradiation, H\u2082S as reductant, sequential HCN addition and photoreduction steps"}, "mechanism": "The cyclic guanidinium hemiaminal undergoes ring-opening and HCN addition (Kiliani-Fischer chain extension), followed by further UV-driven photoreduction by H\u2082S to yield an \u03b1-hydroxythioamide that cyclizes to a \u03b3-butyrothiolactam intermediate. Additional reduction and HCN addition produce compound 46, the \u03b1-aminonitrile direct precursor to arginine.", "reasoning": "Patel et al. (2015) describe this multi-step homologation as the final chain-building sequence in the arginine branch. The Kiliani-Fischer mechanism extends the carbon chain by one carbon per HCN addition. Individual steps are reported with good to excellent yields. Compound 46 is the penultimate intermediate before hydrolysis to arginine."}, {"id": "rxn_012", "name": "Alkaline hydrolysis of \u03b1-aminonitrile (compound 46) to arginine", "inputs": ["mol_014"], "outputs": ["mol_015"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": null, "aqueous": "true", "other": "Alkaline pH (pH 9-11), extended time for nitrile hydrolysis"}, "mechanism": "The \u03b1-aminonitrile (compound 46) undergoes stepwise hydrolysis: R\u2013CN + H\u2082O \u2192 R\u2013C(=O)NH\u2082 (amide) + H\u2082O \u2192 R\u2013COOH (carboxylic acid). The result is free arginine. This is a standard Strecker completion step.", "reasoning": "Hydrolysis of aminonitriles to amino acids is the final step in all Strecker-type syntheses and is well-established (Miller, 1986). Patel et al. (2015) note that compound 46 would hydrolyze to arginine under alkaline aqueous conditions. The alkaline pH found in prebiotic pools or alkaline vent outflow facilitates this hydrolysis."}, {"id": "rxn_013", "name": "Hydrothermal CO\u2082 fixation to \u03b1-ketoglutarate on greigite/magnetite", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_016"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)", "magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084), magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)", "aqueous": "true", "other": "Alkaline hydrothermal vent, reductive CO\u2082 fixation via proto-rTCA cycle steps"}, "mechanism": "Multiple sequential CO\u2082 fixation and reduction steps on Fe-S mineral surfaces build up the C5 dicarboxylic acid skeleton. CO\u2082 \u2192 formate \u2192 acetate \u2192 pyruvate \u2192 oxaloacetate \u2192 \u03b1-ketoglutarate, with each step catalyzed by greigite and/or magnetite. This mimics the reductive tricarboxylic acid cycle.", "reasoning": "Hydrothermal CO\u2082 fixation to multi-carbon keto acids via a proto-rTCA cycle has been proposed as a key metabolic origin pathway (W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user, 1990; Smith & Morowitz, 2004). Recent work by Muchowska et al. (2017) demonstrated Fe(0)-promoted reductive carboxylation producing TCA intermediates including \u03b1-ketoglutarate. This provides the C5 backbone for the metabolic-analog route to arginine (Glavin et al., 2025)."}, {"id": "rxn_014", "name": "Reductive amination of \u03b1-ketoglutarate to glutamate on FeS/NiS", "inputs": ["mol_016", "mol_003"], "outputs": ["mol_017"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["pyrite (FeS\u2082)", "mackinawite (FeS)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "FeS/NiS surfaces", "aqueous": "true", "other": "Excess NH\u2083, acidic to neutral pH, reducing conditions"}, "mechanism": "\u03b1-Ketoglutarate undergoes reductive amination on FeS/NiS surfaces: R\u2013C(=O)\u2013COOH + NH\u2083 + 2[H] \u2192 R\u2013CH(NH\u2082)\u2013COOH + H\u2082O. The mineral surface provides both the template and electron transfer capability. H\u2082 or FeS is the terminal reductant.", "reasoning": "Huber & W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user (2003) demonstrated reductive amination of \u03b1-keto acids to \u03b1-amino acids on FeS/NiS surfaces under hydrothermal conditions. Glutamate is a central metabolic amino acid and the starting point for the ornithine/citrulline/arginine biosynthetic pathway. Glavin et al. (2025) note glutamate availability in prebiotic ponds could conceivably feed an ornithine \u2192 arginine pathway."}, {"id": "rxn_015", "name": "Glutamate to ornithine via transamination and chain modification", "inputs": ["mol_017", "mol_003"], "outputs": ["mol_018"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": null, "aqueous": "true", "other": "Prebiotic pool, wet-dry cycling for condensation, requires glutamate semialdehyde intermediate"}, "mechanism": "Glutamate is converted to ornithine via a multi-step sequence analogous to biological biosynthesis: glutamate \u2192 N-acetylglutamate \u2192 glutamate semialdehyde \u2192 ornithine. In the prebiotic context, this requires transamination (with a suitable amino donor such as alanine) and partial reduction. The conversion may be inefficient but plausible given excess NH\u2083.", "reasoning": "Biological arginine biosynthesis proceeds through glutamate \u2192 ornithine \u2192 citrulline \u2192 arginine. Glavin et al. (2025) suggest that glutamate availability in prebiotic ponds could feed an ornithine \u2192 citrulline pathway, though this remains speculative. Transamination between amino acids and keto acids is prebiotically plausible on mineral surfaces (Huber & W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user, 2003). This represents the metabolic-analog branch of the arginine network."}, {"id": "rxn_016", "name": "Guanidinylation of ornithine by cyanamide to arginine", "inputs": ["mol_018", "mol_011"], "outputs": ["mol_015"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": null, "aqueous": "true", "other": "Concentrated prebiotic pool, neutral to slightly basic pH"}, "mechanism": "The \u03b4-amino group of ornithine attacks the electrophilic carbon of cyanamide (NH\u2082CN), forming a guanidine linkage: Orn\u2013NH\u2082 + NH\u2082CN \u2192 Orn\u2013NH\u2013C(=NH)\u2013NH\u2082 = arginine. This is a direct =NH transfer reaction.", "reasoning": "Cyanamide is a well-known guanidinylating agent that transfers the =NH fragment to primary amines (Patel et al., 2015). The reaction of ornithine with cyanamide to yield arginine is the most direct metabolic-analog route and has been proposed though not yet demonstrated experimentally (Pol et al., 2022; Glavin et al., 2025). This pathway bypasses the complex cyanosulfidic homologation sequence."}, {"id": "rxn_017", "name": "Carbamoylation of ornithine by urea to citrulline", "inputs": ["mol_018", "mol_020"], "outputs": ["mol_019"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "330-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": null, "aqueous": "true", "other": "Wet-dry cycling to drive condensation, concentrated prebiotic pool"}, "mechanism": "The \u03b4-amino group of ornithine reacts with urea (or the isocyanate derived from its decomposition) to form the ureido linkage of citrulline: Orn\u2013NH\u2082 + (NH\u2082)\u2082CO \u2192 Orn\u2013NH\u2013C(=O)\u2013NH\u2082 + NH\u2083 = citrulline + ammonia.", "reasoning": "Carbamoylation of ornithine to citrulline is the biological route and has been proposed as prebiotically plausible if urea is available (Glavin et al., 2025). Urea can form from NH\u2083 + CO\u2082 under evaporitic conditions. Wet-dry cycling provides the driving force for condensation. This represents the citrulline-mediated branch to arginine."}, {"id": "rxn_018", "name": "Amination of citrulline to arginine", "inputs": ["mol_019", "mol_003"], "outputs": ["mol_015"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": null, "aqueous": "true", "other": "Concentrated prebiotic pool with excess NH\u2083; potentially UV-driven or mineral-catalyzed"}, "mechanism": "Citrulline's ureido group is converted to a guanidino group by condensation with NH\u2083: Cit\u2013NH\u2013C(=O)\u2013NH\u2082 + NH\u2083 \u2192 Arg\u2013NH\u2013C(=NH)\u2013NH\u2082 + H\u2082O. This dehydrative amination replaces the carbonyl oxygen with NH, converting urea to guanidine.", "reasoning": "This is the final step of the biological arginine biosynthetic pathway (argininosuccinate synthetase/lyase in biology). Prebiotically, the conversion of a ureido to guanidino group by amination is thermodynamically challenging but could be driven by excess NH\u2083 and dehydrating conditions (Glavin et al., 2025). This step remains speculative and represents one of the major open challenges in prebiotic arginine synthesis (Pol et al., 2022)."}], "pathways": [{"pathway_id": "P1", "name": "Full cyanosulfidic route from hydrothermal CO\u2082 via formate and formaldehyde", "description": "CO\u2082 is reduced to formate and then formaldehyde in hydrothermal vents. Formaldehyde is transported to surface UV pools where it reacts with NH\u2083 to form HCN. HCN then enters the Patel et al. cyanosulfidic homologation pathway: HCN + acetylene \u2192 acrylonitrile \u2192 \u03b2-aminopropionitrile \u2192 \u03b2-aminopropionaldehyde \u2192 guanidinium hemiaminal \u2192 compound 46 \u2192 arginine.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_002", "rxn_003", "rxn_005", "rxn_006", "rxn_007", "rxn_010", "rxn_011", "rxn_012"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_007", "mol_008", "mol_004", "mol_009", "mol_010", "mol_014"]}, {"pathway_id": "P2", "name": "Direct cyanosulfidic pathway from exogenous HCN", "description": "Starting from prebiotically available HCN (e.g. from atmospheric photochemistry or impact delivery), the full Patel et al. (2015) cyanosulfidic sequence produces arginine via acrylonitrile, \u03b2-aminopropionitrile, and compound 46.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_005", "rxn_006", "rxn_007", "rxn_010", "rxn_011", "rxn_012"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_009", "mol_010", "mol_012", "mol_013", "mol_014"]}, {"pathway_id": "P3", "name": "Hydrothermal HCN source feeding cyanosulfidic pathway", "description": "HCN is generated hydrothermally from CO\u2082 + NH\u2083 + H\u2082 on pyrite/mackinawite surfaces, then transported to surface UV pools to enter the cyanosulfidic acrylonitrile \u2192 arginine sequence.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_004", "rxn_005", "rxn_006", "rxn_007", "rxn_010", "rxn_011", "rxn_012"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_004", "mol_009", "mol_010", "mol_014"]}, {"pathway_id": "P4", "name": "Cyanamide generation via urea feeding guanidinium installation", "description": "CO\u2082 + NH\u2083 form urea in evaporitic pools, which decomposes to cyanamide. Cyanamide then joins the cyanosulfidic pathway at the guanidinium hemiaminal step, providing the guanidine functionality of arginine.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_008", "rxn_009", "rxn_010", "rxn_011", "rxn_012"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_020", "mol_011", "mol_013", "mol_014"]}, {"pathway_id": "P5", "name": "Metabolic-analog pathway: glutamate \u2192 ornithine \u2192 arginine via cyanamide", "description": "Hydrothermal CO\u2082 fixation produces \u03b1-ketoglutarate, which is reductively aminated to glutamate. Glutamate is converted to ornithine, and ornithine is directly guanidinylated by cyanamide to yield arginine.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_013", "rxn_014", "rxn_015", "rxn_016"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_016", "mol_017", "mol_018", "mol_011"]}, {"pathway_id": "P6", "name": "Metabolic-analog pathway: glutamate \u2192 ornithine \u2192 citrulline \u2192 arginine", "description": "The full biosynthetic analog: hydrothermal glutamate \u2192 ornithine \u2192 citrulline (via urea carbamoylation) \u2192 arginine (via amination). This is the most metabolically faithful but least experimentally supported route.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_013", "rxn_014", "rxn_015", "rxn_017", "rxn_018"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_016", "mol_017", "mol_018", "mol_019"]}, {"pathway_id": "P7", "name": "Hydrothermal HCN \u2192 cyanamide \u2192 ornithine guanidinylation", "description": "HCN is generated hydrothermally, transported to surface pools where it feeds urea/cyanamide generation. Independently, ornithine is produced from the metabolic-analog branch. Cyanamide then guanidinylates ornithine to yield arginine.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_004", "rxn_008", "rxn_009", "rxn_013", "rxn_014", "rxn_015", "rxn_016"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_004", "mol_011", "mol_018"]}, {"pathway_id": "P8", "name": "Formaldehyde-derived HCN \u2192 acrylonitrile shortcut", "description": "Hydrothermal formaldehyde (from formate reduction) is converted to HCN at the surface, which directly couples with acetylene to enter the cyanosulfidic pathway. This route bypasses direct CO\u2082-to-HCN conversion.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_002", "rxn_003", "rxn_005", "rxn_006", "rxn_007", "rxn_010", "rxn_011", "rxn_012"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_008", "mol_004", "mol_009"]}, {"pathway_id": "P9", "name": "Urea-mediated citrulline pathway from surface chemistry", "description": "Urea is generated from NH\u2083 + CO\u2082 in evaporitic pools. Independently, ornithine arrives from the metabolic branch. Urea directly carbamoylates ornithine to citrulline, which is then aminated to arginine.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_008", "rxn_013", "rxn_014", "rxn_015", "rxn_017", "rxn_018"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_020", "mol_018", "mol_019"]}, {"pathway_id": "P10", "name": "Convergent hydrothermal-surface network to arginine via compound 46", "description": "Both hydrothermal and surface HCN sources converge: hydrothermal CO\u2082 \u2192 formate \u2192 formaldehyde \u2192 HCN merges with hydrothermal CO\u2082 + NH\u2083 \u2192 HCN. Meanwhile, CO\u2082 + NH\u2083 \u2192 urea \u2192 cyanamide is generated independently. All converge in surface UV pools for the cyanosulfidic homologation: acrylonitrile \u2192 compound 46 \u2192 arginine. This represents the maximally interconnected route.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_002", "rxn_003", "rxn_004", "rxn_005", "rxn_006", "rxn_007", "rxn_008", "rxn_009", "rxn_010", "rxn_011", "rxn_012"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_004", "mol_009", "mol_011", "mol_014"]}], "hub_molecules": ["mol_004", "mol_009", "mol_011", "mol_018", "mol_020"], "convergence_points": [{"molecule_id": "mol_004", "description": "HCN is